a</b> ‘descendant of <i>Eodhus</i>’. This was the name of a bardic family associated with the Maguires of Fermanagh, also Anglicized as   Oswell   or   Oswald  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Hosea","meanings":["English: variant of   Hussey  . Similarity with the Old Testament prophet's name Hosea (see 3 below) is accidental.","English: in Scotland, where the name is more common, it is sometimes a variant of   Hosie  , itself a form of   Hussey  , or else a variant of   Hossack  .","African (mainly Nigeria and Tanzania): from the Biblical personal name <i>Hosea</i>. In the Old Testament, Hosea was a prophet who married a prostitute in order to illustrate Israel's unfaithfulness to God."]},{"name":"Hosie","meanings":["Scottish (northeast Scotland): variant of Irish   Hussey  ."]},{"name":"Hassey","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Hussey  ."]},{"name":"Oswell","meanings":["English: variant of   Oswald  .","Irish (Ulster): adopted as an English equivalent of Gaelic <b>Ó hEodhusa</b> ‘descendant of <i>Eodhus</i>’ (see   Hussey  )."]},{"name":"Hosey","meanings":["English: variant of   Hussey  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Hussey was born in 1492, in Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom. She married John Ballard in 1515. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1520, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 28."},"et":{"1492–1520":"1492–1520","1482–1567":"1482–1567","1518–1605":"1518–1605","1567":"1567","1520":"1520","1482":"1482","1492":"1492","1518":"1518","1605":"1605","1515":"1515","Abt. 1518":"umbes 1518","Nottinghamshire, England":"Nottinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Middleton Cheney, Northamptonshi